lexUnit.name: rap.v
lexUnit.definition: COD: strike (a hard surface) with a series of rapid audible blows.

sentence.text: His hand rapped the door frame and he gave a chirrup of pain .
He rapped the desk .
Drawing a long , thin stiletto from his belt , he rapped the top of the table .
Benjamin rapped the top of the table .
Of course , the Rolls-Royce limousine was his , and he rapped sharply on the window to waken the sleeping chauffeur .
He rapped gently on the wood .
They Rapped vigorously at the furniture to get the dust out .
But before he had completed his swing the boy fearfully withdrew his arm and the cane rapped harmlessly on the floor .
My friend went on down the winding road for about two miles , finishing at the quayside , where he rapped smartly on a door .
Meredith hesitated again in the porch and then rapped loudly on it .
He rapped three times on the door of Room 144 , it was opened a few inches .
Bullets from somewhere rapped his own aircraft , and then he was hurdling the bomber and flattening out above the battered grass of the field .
Leafless twigs rapped their faces like bony knuckles .
Before I lifted the knocker I gave my clogs an extra rub on my stockinged calf , then I rapped on the door .
Probably be glad to get rid of her , she thought gloomily , then looked up sharply as someone rapped at the back door .
Angrily she rapped on his window .
Then his shoulders rapped against granite , scoring the flesh , and he was bounced upright .
Creed went over and rapped on the top section , but there was no answer .
The small stones rapped under their feet .
Cally rapped on the Suzuki 's passenger window and he thought twice about leaning across and unlocking the door .
